WEBVTT

00:00:00.250 --> 00:00:04.546
Introducing; Improving low vision chart
accessibility via on cursor visual context.

00:00:05.130 --> 00:00:07.757
For low vision users,
reading charts is a complex task,

00:00:07.757 --> 00:00:10.802
requiring exhausting panning,
zooming, and mental reconstruction.

00:00:11.094 --> 00:00:13.638
We overlay semantic context
directly around the pointer.

00:00:13.847 --> 00:00:16.108
Our method works together
with existing assistive tools

00:00:16.132 --> 00:00:18.393
and makes accessing charts
easier for low vision users.

00:00:18.435 --> 00:00:21.813
Informed by our formative study, identify
four critical elements for access

00:00:21.855 --> 00:00:25.525
the axes, the legend, the gridlines,
and the overview.

00:00:25.817 --> 00:00:27.569
We explore two interaction paradigms.

00:00:27.569 --> 00:00:31.156
Mini map inspired by overview
plus detail and dynamic context.

00:00:31.156 --> 00:00:33.158
Inspired by focus plus context methods.

00:00:33.158 --> 00:00:36.244
We evaluated these with 22 low vision
participants using a mixed

00:00:36.244 --> 00:00:38.496
methods approach across
diverse chart types.

00:00:38.496 --> 00:00:41.041
Our results show that dynamic context
significantly increases

00:00:41.041 --> 00:00:43.793
the usability of existing assistive tools
for chart exploration.

00:00:43.793 --> 00:00:47.005
We observed a fundamental shift in access
patterns on some visualizations,

00:00:47.130 --> 00:00:49.924
where the way users navigate data change
significantly.

00:00:49.924 --> 00:00:52.385
Dynamic context
significantly reduced both the physical

00:00:52.385 --> 00:00:55.138
and overall effort
required to read and interpret charts.

00:00:55.138 --> 00:00:58.600
While both methods improve access,
dynamic context had a significantly higher

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:01.603
impact on a user's
sense of autonomy and data clarity.

00:01:01.603 --> 00:01:04.355
Dynamic context is an approach
that gives low vision people

00:01:04.355 --> 00:01:07.358
easier access to what
they should see within its context.

00:01:07.942 --> 00:01:10.153
Thank you.
Please read our paper to learn more.